{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141022175551|630680142","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Scott_Tipton","to":"Scott Tipton"}],"pages":{"4176183":{"pageid":4176183,"ns":0,"title":"Scott Tipton","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-10-22T17:55:54Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{BLP sources|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name         = Scott Tipton\n|image        = Scott Tipton, Official Portrait, 112th Congress.JPG\n|state        = [[Colorado]]\n|district     = {{ushr|Colorado|3|3rd}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2011\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[John Salazar]]\n|successor    = \n|state_house1 = Colorado\n|district1    = 58th\n|term_start1  = January 9, 2009\n|term_end1    = January 2, 2011\n|predecessor1 = Ray Rose\n|successor1   = Don Coram\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|11|9}}\n|birth_place  = [[Espa\u00f1ola, New Mexico|Espa\u00f1ola]], [[New Mexico]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Jean Tipton\n|children     = Liesl<br>Elizabeth\n|alma_mater   = [[Fort Lewis College]]\n|religion     = [[Anglican]]\n|website      = [http://www.votetipton.com/ campaign website]\n}}\n'''Scott R. Tipton''' (born November 9, 1956) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|CO|3}}. In November 2010, he defeated three-term, [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[John Salazar]], whom he lost to by a wide margin, in 2006. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He was a member of the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] and a co-owner of a pottery company in [[Cortez, Colorado]]. Prior to being elected to public office, he was chairman of the [[Colorado Republican Party]], from 1997 to 2008.\n\n==Early life==\nTipton was raised in [[Cortez, Colorado|Cortez]], where he attended public schools with his brother Joe and graduated from [[Montezuma-Cortez High School]]. He went on to [[Fort Lewis College|Ft. Lewis College]] in [[Durango, Colorado|Durango]] where he studied [[political science]] and graduated in 1978. After Ft. Lewis, he returned to Cortez and founded Mesa Verde Indian Pottery, which he co-owns with his brother, Joe. {{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\n==Early political career==\nA lifelong Republican, he became involved in the unsuccessful [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 1976|Reagan presidential campaign of 1976]] and was a delegate to the Republican Convention that year. He also assisted with local campaigns for Reagan in 1980 and 1984 across [[Montezuma County|Montezuma County, Colorado]] and the 3rd Congressional district.\n\nHe held various roles for the campaigns of [[Scott McInnis]], Ben Campbell, Bill Owens and [[George W. Bush]]. A former Montezuma County Republican chairman, he was also the party chairman of the 3rd Congressional District for eight years.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}\n\n==Colorado legislature==\n===2008 election===\nOn February 5, 2008, he announced his candidacy for the Colorado House seat representing District 58. The announcement came shortly after the incumbent, Ray Rose, announced he would retire in 2008. He had no opposition in the Republican primary,<ref name=\"prim08\">{{cite web |url=http://rs.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=syj1hm55hso5ty55pcuhyprg&ControlID=a61fb386-685c-4a0c-a691-71334ad539d8&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=ClientControllerdnn_ctr370_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&EnableFindNext=False&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 Primary Election |accessdate=2008-11-08 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}</ref> but faced Democratic candidate Noelle Hagan in the November 2008 general election. Hagan's candidacy was endorsed by the ''[[Denver Post]]''<ref name=\"dphouse\">{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Post's picks in Colorado's House of Representatives |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_10741559 |work=Denver Post |date=17 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-09 }}\n</ref> and the ''Montrose Daily Press'',\n<ref name=\"csind\">{{cite news |first=Wendy |last=Norris |author2=Bob Spencer  |title=State candidate endorsement watch |url=http://coloradoindependent.com/11911/state-candidate-endorsement-watch |work=Colorado Independent |date=3 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-09 }}</ref> but Tipton won the with 59 percent of the vote.<ref name=\"gen08\">{{cite web |url=http://coreports.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=jexpso55dlbays450fyzrmb4&ControlID=3a1b317069f040849b2b689d78addfc9&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=dnn_ctr376_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&SearchStartPage=0&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 General Election |accessdate=2008-12-04 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nWith Representatives [[Laura Bradford]] and [[Frank McNulty (Colorado legislator)|Frank McNulty]], Tipton planned on re-introducing a version of [[Jessica's Law]] to establish minimum sentences for [[child sex offender]]s,<ref name=\"jess\">{{cite news |first=Emily |last=Anderson |title=Jessica's Law bill gets state sponsors |url=http://www.postindependent.com/article/20081125/COMMUNITY_NEWS/811249962 |work=Grand Junction Free Press |date=24 November 2008 |accessdate=27 January 2014 }}</ref> sponsoring bills to create a full-time judge position in [[Montrose, Colorado|Montrose]]<ref name=\"tipissues\">{{cite news |first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=Rep. Tipton's issues include roads, sexual assault, education |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20110728120701/http://www.cortezjournal.com/Main.asp?SectionID=1&SubSectionID=1&ArticleID=3813 |work=Cortez Journal |date=24 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-27 }}</ref><ref name=\"woes\">{{cite news |first=K.C. |last=Mason |title=Budget Woes Will Handcuff Colorado Legislature |url=http://www.telluridewatch.com/pages/full_story?page_label=news&id=1253738-Budget-Woes-Will-Handcuff-Colorado-Legislature&widget=push&instance=secondary_stories_left_column&article-Budget-Woes-Will-Handcuff-Colorado-Legislature%20=&open=& |work=Telluride Watch |date=7 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-01-10 }}</ref> and to simplify water rights filing.<ref name=\"ahern\">{{cite news |first=Reilly |last=Capps |title=Ahern may give it another go |url=http://www.telluridenews.com/articles/2009/01/12/news/doc496be8bcf23ab611488556.txt |work=Telluride Daily Planet |date=12 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-04 }}</ref> The attempt to introduce a version of Jessica's Law was unsuccessful, it dying in committee.<ref name=\"ahern\">{{cite news |first=Reilly |last=Capps |title=Political accusations fly after Colorado's \"Jessica's Law\" dies|url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_22670788/political-accusations-fly-after-colorados-jessicas-law-dies |work=Telluride The Denver Post |date=26 February 2009 |accessdate=27 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nFor the 2009 legislative session, Tipton was named to seats on the House Agriculture, Livestock, and Natural Resources Committee and the House Local Government Committee.<ref name=\"cmte09\">{{cite press release |title=House Republican Committee Assignments Announced |date=18 November 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://www.coloradohousegop.com/?q=node/92 }}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n;2006\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2006#District 3}}\nHe unsuccessfully challenged the then, first term, [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic]] U.S. congressman, [[John Salazar]].  Tipton lost 38% to 62% for Salazar.<ref>{{cite news | first = Gary | last = Harmon | title = Salazar-Tipton rematch a different contest | date = 2010-08-03 | url = http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/articles/salazartipson_rematch_a_differ | work = [[Grand Junction Daily Sentinel]] | accessdate = 2010-10-28}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2010#District 3}}\nHe again challenged Democratic incumbent [[John Salazar]] in {{ushr|CO|3}}. [[Libertarian Party (US)|Libertarian]] Gregory Gilman and independent Jake Segrest were also on the ballot, with independents John W. Hargis, Sr. and James Fritz qualified as write-in candidates. He decided to retire from the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] to run for Congress in 2010, again challenging Salazar.<ref name=tipton>{{cite web | url = http://www.rollcall.com/news/40479-1.html?type=printer_friendly | title = Tipton Joins Race Against Salazar | author = Greg Giroux | publisher = Roll Call | date = 2009-11-09 | accessdate = 2009-11-25}}</ref> In the Republican primary, he defeated Bob McConnell 56% to 44%.<ref>{{cite news | first = Mike | last = Lawrence | title = Steamboat\u2019s McConnell defeated in District 3, Scott Tipton wins GOP congressional primary, goes on to face Rep. John Salazar | date = 2010-08-10 | url = http://www.steamboatpilot.com/news/2010/aug/10/tough-loss-steamboats-bob-mcconnell/ | work = [[Steamboat Pilot & Today|Steamboat Pilot]] | accessdate = 2010-10-28 | quote = With 70 percent of precincts reporting results Tuesday night, Tipton, a state representative from Cortez, had received 56 percent of votes across the 3rd Congressional District, compared with about 44 percent for McConnell. }}</ref> In the general election, he defeated Salazar 50.10% to 45.76%.\n\n;2012\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Colorado, 2012#District 3}}\nIn 2012, he was challenged by [[Sal Pace]], a [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] state representative from [[Pueblo, Colorado|Pueblo]]. His re-election campaign was aided by $1.3 million in advertising against Pace, funded by the [[Grover Norquist]] led, [[Americans for Tax Reform]].<ref name=Norquist>{{cite news|title=ATR Announces 1.3 Million Dollar Ad Buy in Colorado\u2019s 3rd Congressional District|url=http://www.atr.org/atr-announces-point-million-dollar-ad-a7247|accessdate=30 Oct 2012|date=12 Oct 2012}}</ref> SG Interests, an oil and gas company from Texas, that sought to drill in the Thompson Divide area, also campaigned against Pace.<ref name=SG>{{cite news|title=Driller starts super PAC to support Tipton|url=http://www.durangoherald.com/article/20121029/NEWS01/121029486/Driller-starts-super-PAC-to-support-Tipton--|accessdate=30 Oct 2012|date=29 Oct 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nHe has signed [[Grover Norquist]]'s [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]].<ref name =\"ATR\">{{cite web|title=The Taxpayer Protection Pledge Signers 112th Congressional List|url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/atrfiles/files/files/091411-federalpledgesigners.pdf|publisher=Americans for Tax Reform|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> He has also supported the [[The Path to Prosperity|Ryan Plan]], having twice voted for it.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.chieftain.com/news/local/tipton-defends-gop-approach/article_4a4ef9e0-6266-11e0-bbbd-001cc4c002e0.html | title = Tipton defends GOP approach | author = Peter Roper | publisher = Pueblo Chieftain | date = 2011-04-09 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 Tipton signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Tipton_Scott.pdf</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry|Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands|Subcommittee on National Parks, Forests and Public Lands]]\n**[[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Water and Power|Subcommittee on Water and Power]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Committee on Small Business]]'''\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade|Subcommittee on Agriculture, Energy and Trade]], chairman\n**[[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations|Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations]]\n\n===Legislation===\nTipton introduced the [[Water Rights Protection Act (H.R. 3189; 113th Congress)]] into the House on September 26, 2013. The bill would prevent federal agencies from requiring certain entities to relinquish their water rights to the United States in order to use [[public lands]].<ref name=3189cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 3189 - CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/44956|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> Tipton said the bill was needed because it \"provides critical protection for water rights' holders from federal takings by ensuring that federal government agencies cannot extort private property rights through uneven-handed negotiations.\"<ref name=COtiptonbill>{{cite news|last=Hudson|first=Audrey|title=Tipton Bill Seeks to Stop Feds from Trampling Water Rights|url=http://thecoloradoobserver.com/2013/10/tipton-bill-seeks-to-stop-feds-from-trampling-water-rights/|accessdate=12 March 2014|newspaper=The Colorado Observer|date=11 October 2013}}</ref> Tipton argued that the bill \"prohibits federal agencies from pilfering water rights through the use of permits, leases, and other land management arrangements, for which it would otherwise have to pay just compensation under the 5th Amendment of the Constitution.\"<ref name=\"COtiptonbill\"/>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2011, it was reported that he spent over $7,000 on vendors that did business with his nephew's company.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/colo-rep-tipton-facing-second-ethics-issue | title = Colo. Rep. Tipton Facing Second Ethics Issue | publisher = TheDenverChannel.com | date = 2011-06-09 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref> Also in 2011, Tipton wrote an apology letter to the [[House Ethics Committee]] after it became known that his daughter was using his name in an effort to secure government contracts from other Congressional offices.  In 2012, he violated House rules when his office mistakenly used taxpayer resources to promote a campaign event.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_20084097 | title = Rep. Tipton violates House rules in promoting campaign event | author = Allison Sherry | publisher = The Denver Post | date = 2012-03-02 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref>\n\nA [[super PAC]], funded by oil and gas driller SG Interests, is registered at the address of Tipton\u2019s campaign attorney and run by a law clerk in his office.  Although it is a violation of election laws for super PACs and a candidate's campaign to coordinate their activities, Tipton's attorney said: \u201cI have specifically put up Chinese walls to make sure Charlie (law clerk) is in no way involved with the Tipton campaign, and I\u2019m in no way involved with the Colorado Future Fund.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.durangoherald.com/article/20121029/NEWS01/121029486/Driller-starts-super-PAC-to-support-Tipton-- | title = Driller starts super PAC to support Tipton | publisher = Durango Herald | date = 2012-10-29 | accessdate = 2012-10-30}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe and Jean Tipton have been married for over 30 years. They have two daughters, Liesl and Elizabeth.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}\n\n==References==\n<div class=\"references-small\">\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n</div>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://tipton.house.gov/ Congressman Scott Tipton] official U.S. House site\n*[http://votetipton.com/ Scott Tipton for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Colorado/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Scott_Tipton_%5BR-3%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = T000470 | ballot = Scott_Tipton | nndb = 949/000266151 | votesmart = 65403 | govtrack = 412405 | opencong = 412405 | rollcall = 25488 | politifact = | ontheissues = House/Scott_Tipton.htm | congress = scott-tipton/1997 | worldcat = | fec = H6CO03139 | opensecrets = N00027509 | assets = scott-tipton | legistorm = 2734/Rep_Scott_Tipton_CO.html | followthemoney = 8367 | c-span = scotttipton | rose = | imdb = | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAxnpVKP }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Salazar]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Colorado|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Colorado's 3rd congressional district]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Stivers]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=337th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Daniel Webster (Florida politician)|Daniel Webster]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{CO-FedRep}}\n\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n| NAME              =Tipton, Scott\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     =1956-11-09\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    =[[Cortez, Colorado]]\n|